McKinsey Sales Excellence Hackathon

The business problem is to predict loan approval, given applicant details like income, debt and demographics.

Exploratory Data Analysis

We start with EDA and list down some of the key observations made, while the basis for the same is displayed in the calls below.
###Key observations
Approved is continuous. Change to categorical.
Too many NA in EMI, Interest_Rate, Loan_Period, Loan_Amount. Omit columns?
51 NA in Existing_EMI. Omit rows?
Unlabelled levels in Primary_Bank_Type. Add name?
Unlabelled levels in Employer_Category1, Employer_Code, City_Category. Add name? Make categorical.
Skewed distributions for Existing_EMI and Monthly_Income. Transform - bin/ bound/ log etc.
Change DOB to Age. 15 rows without DOB. Delete rows?
Too many levels for City_Code, Employer_Code, Customer_Existing_Primary_Bank_Code. Drop?
The raw Monthly Income and Existing EMI variables are not showing sufficient discerning power.
The DOB variable in its current categorical form is unusable.
The remaining variables are categorical. Further EDA is performed after data processing to address above issues.

EDA on processed data

The raw Monthly Income and Existing EMI variables were not showing sufficient discerning power. After transformation to log form, this has improved. The DOB variable in its current categorical form is unusable. But transformation into the applicants Age shows potential. The remaining variables are categorical. Chi Square tests of independence between each variable and loan approval are conducted. Graphical tests are also provided to visualize the dependence. None of the variables analyzed can be excluded since the null hypothesis of independence have to be rejected due to the low p values.

library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
#Bivariate analysis: Gender v/s Approved
chisq.test(trainData_WIP$Gender, trainData_WIP$Approved)
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity correction
## 
## data:  trainData_WIP$Gender and trainData_WIP$Approved
## X-squared = 141.73, df = 1, p-value < 2.2e-16
trainData_WIP %>% group_by(Gender, Approved) %>% 
  summarise(count=n()) %>% 
  mutate(perc=count/sum(count)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=Gender, y=perc*100, fill=Approved)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity") +
  geom_col(show.legend = T, ) + 
  labs(title="Gender v/s Approved", y="% Approved") +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette="PuRd") +
  coord_flip()

Model training and evaluation

From EDA, we see that of only 1,000 Approvals were given out of about 70,000 applicants. Thats 1.5%. This highly imbalanced dataset creates special problems for our analysis.
Despite much optmization, the running time of the model training code below exceeds 8 hours each. Hence optimization has not been done and much scope remains to further optimize the dataset (like balancing data classes) and model training. The training and the performance of the two iterations (Random Forest and Gradient Boosted Model) executed are shown below.

#check using RF model through caret
set.seed(605)
Control <- trainControl(
  #method = 'repeatedcv', number = 1, repeats = 3, #these values may have changed
                          classProbs = TRUE, summaryFunction = twoClassSummary)
modelRF <- train(Approved~., data = trainData_WIP[,-which(names(trainData_WIP) %in% c('ID'))], 
                 method = 'rf', trControl = Control, metric = 'ROC')

#check using GBM model through caret
fitControl <- trainControl(
  #method = 'repeatedcv', number = 10, repeats = 10, #these values may have changed
                          classProbs = TRUE, summaryFunction = twoClassSummary)
set.seed(605)
modelGBM <- train(Approved~., data = trainData_WIP[,-which(names(trainData_WIP) %in% c('ID'))], 
                  method = 'gbm', trControl = fitControl, metric = 'ROC', verbose = FALSE)

Predictions

Code used to make and save predictions to submit to the hackathon.

RF_results <- predict(modelRF, newdata = testData_WIP)
submission <- cbind(as.character(testData_WIP$ID), RF_results)
submission <- as.data.frame(submission)
names(submission) <- c('ID', 'Approved')
levels(submission$Approved)[levels(submission$Approved) == 1] <- 0
levels(submission$Approved)[levels(submission$Approved) == 2] <- 1
write.csv(submission, file='submission_RF.csv', row.names = FALSE)

#similarly for all other models, inc GBM

Downsampling

A simple downsampling provided interesting insights and improvements. Although Sensitivity continues to be the metric of importance, Specifcity in this case is reasonable. Options to optimize further are listed in the Next Steps section below.

#downsampling
trainDataTrimmed_small <- downSample(x=trainData_WIP[,-which(names(trainData_WIP) %in% 
                                                                  c('ID', 'Approved'))],
                                    y=trainData_WIP$Approved)
Control <- trainControl(
  #method = 'repeatedcv', number = 10, repeats = 3, 
  classProbs = TRUE, summaryFunction = twoClassSummary)
modelRF_downsample <- train(Class~., data = trainDataTrimmed_small[,-which(names(trainDataTrimmed) %in% c('ID'))], 
                 method = 'rf', trControl = Control, metric = 'ROC')

Next steps

There are several avenues to pursue this further, including,
The output of variable importance of the downsampled RF model could be used to trim columns from the dataset and then run training on all the records.
The reason for the very slow model training seems to be the large number of classes (e.g. Source = 29 levels, Customer_Existing_Primary_Bank_Code = 58 levels, and even larger numbers for City and Employer). Many of these are imbalanced as well. Instead ofexcluding from the model, can the classes be combined?
Instead of a 1:1 downsampling that cuts the dataset size to about 2,000, can the frequent class (loan denied) be downsampled to about 10,000 records?

Using functions

To maintain high reuse and repeatability, data pre-processing/ munging has been placed into functions.

McK_pre_proc_train_only <- function (McKSalesData) {
  McKSalesDataTrimmed <- McKSalesData[complete.cases(McKSalesData[,'Existing_EMI']),]# dropping NA rows
  McKSalesDataTrimmed <- McKSalesDataTrimmed[!(McKSalesDataTrimmed$DOB == ''),]
  change_to_fact <- c('Approved')
  McKSalesDataTrimmed[change_to_fact] <- lapply(McKSalesDataTrimmed[change_to_fact], factor)#converting above columns to categorical
  levels(McKSalesDataTrimmed$Approved)[levels(McKSalesDataTrimmed$Approved) == '0'] <- 'NO'
  levels(McKSalesDataTrimmed$Approved)[levels(McKSalesDataTrimmed$Approved) == '1'] <- 'YES'
  McKSalesDataTrimmed
}

McK_pre_proc_test_only <- function (McKSalesData) {
  McKSalesData$Existing_EMI[is.na(McKSalesData$Existing_EMI)] <- 1 ## dummy value for NA rows in test data
  levels(McKSalesData$DOB)[levels(McKSalesData$DOB) == ''] <- '01/01/2000' ## dummy value for blank rows in test data
  McKSalesData
}

calc_age <- function(birthDate, refDate = Sys.Date()) {           #function that calculates years since a given date 
                                                                  #to current/ system date (reused code found on github)
  require(lubridate)
  period <- as.period(interval(birthDate, refDate), unit = "year")
  period$year
}

McK_pre_proc_common <- function (McKSalesData) {
  #dropping less informative columns
  drops <- c('EMI', 'Interest_Rate', 'Loan_Period', 'Loan_Amount', "Lead_Age", 'Employer_Code', 'City_Code', 
             'Lead_Creation_Date', 'Customer_Existing_Primary_Bank_Code', 'Source') #picking less informative columns
  McKSalesDataTrimmed <- McKSalesData[,!names(McKSalesData) %in% drops] #dropping above columns
  McKSalesDataTrimmed$Employer_Category2[is.na(McKSalesDataTrimmed$Employer_Category2)] <- 'EC2' #fixing NA in a variable before making it categorical
  #converting these columns to categorical
  change_to_fact <- c('Var1', 'Employer_Category2')
  McKSalesDataTrimmed[change_to_fact] <- lapply(McKSalesDataTrimmed[change_to_fact], factor)
  #Unlabelled levels fix
  levels(McKSalesDataTrimmed$Primary_Bank_Type)[levels(McKSalesDataTrimmed$Primary_Bank_Type) == ''] <- 'PBT'
  levels(McKSalesDataTrimmed$Employer_Category1)[levels(McKSalesDataTrimmed$Employer_Category1) == ''] <- 'EC1'
  levels(McKSalesDataTrimmed$City_Category)[levels(McKSalesDataTrimmed$City_Category) == ''] <- 'CC'
  #transforming continous variables (other transformations like upper bound, exp and sqrt tested and rejected)
  #the +1 is because of zeros in the data and we need to prevent the invalid log of zero calculation
  McKSalesDataTrimmed$Monthly_Income_log <- log(McKSalesDataTrimmed$Monthly_Income+1)
  McKSalesDataTrimmed$Existing_EMI_log <- log(McKSalesDataTrimmed$Existing_EMI+1)
  drops_trfm <- c('Existing_EMI', 'Monthly_Income')
  McKSalesDataTrimmed <- McKSalesDataTrimmed[,!names(McKSalesDataTrimmed) %in% drops_trfm] #dropping the original/ untransformed columns
  #transforming the 'DOB' continous variable to 'Age'. Several ages are negative (POSIX standards issue with converting yy to YYYY format) and need to be fixed.
  McKSalesDataTrimmed$Age <- calc_age(as.Date(McKSalesDataTrimmed$DOB, format = '%d/%m/%y'))
  neg_age_index <- as.Date(McKSalesDataTrimmed$DOB, format = '%d/%m/%y') > Sys.Date()
  McKSalesDataTrimmed$Age[neg_age_index] <- McKSalesDataTrimmed$Age[neg_age_index]+100
  McKSalesDataTrimmed <- McKSalesDataTrimmed[,!names(McKSalesDataTrimmed) %in% c("DOB")] #dropping DOB columns
  McKSalesDataTrimmed
}
